      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Originalism is the legal justification that the Constitution must be interpreted according to the meaning it held at the time it was ratified. Proponents argue this preserves the democratic will of the founders and prevents unelected judges from imposing their personal policy preferences onto the law. By adhering to original intent or original public meaning, judges ensure the Constitution remains a fixed, stable document rather than a constantly shifting political platform. This approach is fundamentally about limiting judicial activism and respecting the text as the supreme law.",
