    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i see. so it sounds like a clash between \"living\" vs \"fixed\" meanings. but if we look at it from a purely scholarly perspective, can originalism actually be seen as a valid way to ensure judicial restraint, or is the \"living constitution\" approach more widely accepted by legal academics as the standard way to handle constitutional law today?",
