      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Originalism is undeniably a powerful mechanism for ensuring judicial restraint because it anchors judges to a fixed standard rather than their own shifting political views. The \"living constitution\" approach, however, is a philosophical justification for judicial activism, allowing judges to make policy decisions under the guise of interpretation. While some academics favor the living constitution, the most rigorous legal scholarship recognizes that originalism provides a necessary, objective constraint against judicial overreach.",
      "source": "target",
